All four areas of your app hit .NET 11 breaking changes. Here's what breaks and how to fix each:

---

### 1. GZipStream empty payload (Medium)
GZipStream now writes headers/footers even with no data. Your zero-byte check will never trigger.

**Fix:** Check uncompressed byte count instead of output stream length:
```csharp
// Before (.NET 10): ms.Length == 0 meant "no data"
// After (.NET 11): ms.Length > 0 even with no data written
// Fix: track whether you actually wrote anything
```

### 2. TAR header checksum validation (Medium)
TAR-reading APIs now **verify checksums**. Your legacy hand-crafted archives with invalid checksums will throw.

**Fix:** Add error handling around `TarReader.GetNextEntry()`:
```csharp
try {
    var entry = reader.GetNextEntry();
} catch (InvalidDataException ex) {
    // Handle invalid/legacy TAR files
}
```
Or fix the legacy tool to emit valid checksums.

### 3. ZipArchive.CreateAsync eager loading (Low)
`CreateAsync` now **eagerly loads** all entries instead of lazily. For your large ZIP files, this increases memory usage since all entries load upfront.

**Fix:** Monitor memory usage; consider streaming or processing entries incrementally if memory pressure becomes an issue.

### 4. MemoryStream maximum capacity (Medium)
Maximum capacity and exception behavior changed. Your large allocations near the limit may now throw **different exception types** or at **different thresholds**.

**Fix:** Review code that catches specific exception types (e.g., `OutOfMemoryException`) around large `MemoryStream` allocations and update the handling.

---

**Bonus:** .NET 11 also now validates **CRC32 checksums** when reading ZIP entries — if any of your large ZIPs are corrupt/truncated, they'll throw `InvalidDataException` too.

